However, there are significant differences in how COVID deaths are reported between countries (https://observatoryihr.org/news/chinarussia-brazil-and-the-underreporting-of-covid19-cases)

  • Variations in testing access, diagnostic capacity and how COVID deaths are defined can lead to significant under reporting of COVID deaths.

  • Deaths may be misattributed to covid19 and, conversely, deaths may not be correctly allocated to covid19 despite being the underlying cause. This contributes to uncertainty in true number of covid19 deaths.

Excess mortality provides an estimate of the additional number of deaths for specified location and time period, compared to the number of deaths expected (often estimated using the same time period in the preceding year or averaged over several preceding years).

  • encompasses deaths from all causes and thus overcomes the variation between countries in reporting and testing of covid19 and in the misclassification of the cause of death. averaged over several preceding years).

  • counts those deaths caused both directly and indirectly by covid19 and gives a summary measure of the whole system impact.

  • To consider the impact of COVID-19, the mortality rate for year 2020, week \(t\) and age \(x\), can be represented by \[m^o_{x, t}\] and is assumed to be a result of the direct effects of COVID-19 (deaths attributable to it) and the indirect knock-on effects on health systems and society. These indirect effects impact the number of deaths due to other natural as well as external causes. The hypothetical or counterfactual no-COVID-19 scenario has expected mortality rate \[m^e_{x, t}\] which is estimated as the average of the most recent death rates (prior to the pandemic) or the forecast of historical rates to 2020. Excess mortality, represented by \(\mu_{x, t}\), can thus be defined as the difference: \[ \mu_{x, t} = m^o_{x, t} - m^e_{x, t} \] evaluated in rate-space to account for population changes and estimated as an absolute rate difference or percentage change. This gives a more comprehensive picture of how a location has been affected by the disease. The key considerations to make when tracking excess mortality are thus:

    • A complete, timely and reliable quantification of the observed deaths \(m^o_{x, t}\). In the case where sentinal surveillance sites or sample surveys are used, or where the routine mortality surveillance systems have known systematic or random bias, adjustments for under-reporting would be required.

    • A robust estimate of expected deaths \(m^e_{x, t}\). Over time, deaths are expected to change according to the population and epidemiological effects unrelated to the pandemic. It is important to capture the underlying secular trend in the mortality data as well as to incorporate any knowledge about seasonal spikes and mortality shocks that would impact recent mortality levels and trends. Crises like wars and natural disasters (floods, earth-quakes etc) could lead to spikes in mortality or displacement of population leading to increased deaths due to a larger population exposed (and necessarily increased risk). In general, the flu-season of the winter months will likely have higher mortality than other times in the year. The expected mortality level and trend should account for the specific components of the mortality profile.

  • The plots below compare the observed and expected all-cause deaths (in the absence of covid19), and the covid19 deaths for the 5-countries with the highest absolute covid19 burden. As the data for the USA suggests, there are potentialy a significant number of deaths that have been experienced beyond the sum of the expected and the observed COVID and thus giving a clearer picture of the impact of the pandemic over time.

We can summarise the expected all-cause, observed all-cause and cause-specific covid19 deaths for 2020 aggregating across all time periods for the year for which observed data are available. The ratio of excess against covid19 mortality can then be calculated for all time points with data for the year and the ratio then used to complete the time-series and predict the excess to the end of the year based on the full-time series of covid19 deaths. Plots shown are for the countries with the highest numbers of covid19 deaths reported over the year. The plot highlights that considering the high covid19 burden for countries such as India, Argentina, Indonesia and Turkey - there potentially is a hidden layer of deaths indirectly caused by covid19 that could be identified if a reliable estimate of excess mortality can be generated.

EURO excess deaths

As an example we can do a preliminary analysis of excess deaths in the EURO region for which death are close to complete. Assuming the average of the 2015-2019 estimates the expected levels sufficiently, we can generate estimates of excess and also consider the covid19 mortality. Of interest are the large number of deaths experienced in the first and second waves of the pandemic as highlighted in the Economist.
